Toronto - A diversity, equity and inclusion employee from a company called, KOJO, shamed and berated a  Toronto principle, Richard Bilkszto, to suicide. 

He was bullied by the employee, Kike Ojo-Thompson, in multiple sessions, who called him a white supremacist and made other disparaging remarks. The school administrator etc would not help him. 

Following the second training session, Bilkszto apparently experienced a mental health crisis that kept him away from work for a month. 

The situation worsened when the school refused to allow Bilkszto to return to the role he had been employed in prior to his mental health leave.

In a last-ditch effort to force accountability, Bilkszto filed a lawsuit against school administrators. He died before this lawsuit completed. 

Bilkszto, had a 24-year career as a principal and previously taught at an inner-city Buffalo school. And in fact had returned after his retirement they regarded him so highly. 

He was also a Toronto chapter member of the Foundation Against Intolerance and Racism (FAIR), an advocacy group committed to civil rights and anti-discrimination.
